                <p class="lead fw-500 sm-mb-5 m-0">It can be hard to know when hospice is the right choice for a loved one after a stroke. Hospice care may be appropriate when:</p>
            </div>
            <div class="col-lg-6 offset-lg-1 text-center text-lg-start" style="">
                <ul class="p-0 m-0 list-style-03 text-dark-gray fw-500" style="">
                    <li>The patient is unable to perform basic activities of daily living (bathing, dressing, eating) without help</li>
                    <li>There is progressive weight loss or inability to maintain adequate nutrition</li>
                    <li>The patient is mostly bed-bound or chair-bound</li>
                    <li>Speech is severely limited or unintelligible</li>
                    <li>There is a reduced level of consciousness or prolonged coma</li>
                    <li>The patient has stopped curative treatments and has a life expectancy of six months or less, as determined by a physician</li>
                </ul>
                <p class="m-0">Even if your loved one has experienced multiple minor strokes and is declining, early conversations about hospice can help you prepare and make informed decisions.</p>
